column7: Only thing I don't agree with is having scope on toggle. If you're a Jett main then obviously you're going to marshal on save rounds. And it is undoubtedly true that marshal is better with hold. And if you use OP with hold then you can much more aggressivly. TenZ himself said on an old video that if you use hold you feel much more in touch with your operator. The extra pressure is good depending on your grip style because it feels like using a lower sens without actually changing your sens. Makes micro flicks much easier. Because you put pressure on the mouse, the flicks are clean and much more precise. The only time it cause a strain is when you hold an angle for too long, which is not a very good case scenario. I'd much rather continuously scope and rescope.

column3: Its crazy how good Tyson was at cs but he just lacked skills in everything but aim (his other skills were inadequate when comparing it to his aim) compared to new and more experienced pros, he relied on his aim and a game like cs is mostly aim but when the game started evolving to a mind game requiring skills like team synergy, gamesense and mental at the same time Tyson entered the pro scene, he was an insane player that got really unlucky with the timing of the evolving of the pro scene. Same thing with valorant now, he is insanely talented in every given way but he just got unlucky with how fast the pro scene evolved, i mean if you take a look at when he won the vct iceland tournament, he heavily relied on his aim and his ability to carry the team but when other teams and pros caught up they were stuck in the never ending loop of playing good but inadequate for winning any more world championships because TenZ couldnt carry anymore and they needed a new roster that didnt have to always work around his playstyle and his ability to frag out because valorant is 50% aim 20% util usage and 30% team synergy but when you become pro the team synergy and util usage becomes way more important which is a valuable lesson to any upcoming valorant or cs pros with cs2 coming out soon.

column1: When the game and pro scene is young, one exceptional player can single handedly bring their team to the highest level

But after a few years later where the skill gap mechanically are tightened, single amazing player just isn't able to make the same impact as they used to. A team's synergy and decision making dictates the wins they get more consistently.

Usually this means the single great player either evolves to a level that no one can ever reach or he becomes the greatest firepower with a competent IGL (where this could be himself/herself or another player).

column3: I actually like the character, it was rough trying to learn him, his kit really needs you to change your approach and I was getting dogged in my early matches. But he's super fun. Those thin walls have so much potential for plays that you wouldn't even expect, players have to respect those walls or they'd get gunned down if they try to play aorund it. Hes a great character for those who wants to play a offensive wall smoker. The orb can get you into advantageous positions and can be great but risky way for countering aggressions If you treat it like a wall to peek from.

column1: You gotta play around his walls and condition players to respect whatever is behind it. But its bad for teammates who doesn't know how to play around it. He is super strong in taking space and with creativity he can be a fun agent to play around. But as a controller main, I've noticed its hard to play around with a harbor when you both don't agree with the smoke placement.
Personally, if they're gonna buff him, they should make the walls thicker or the slow slightly harsher.
